      suspected, for she contracted a malarial fever in the autumn of 1558, from
      which she did not recover. King Philip sent a message and a ring by Count
      de Feria when he heard of his wife's illness, and proposed that she should
      take measures for the recognition of her sister Elizabeth as her
      successor. Mary complied; and no sooner had she done so than her whole
      court flocked to Hatfield, anxious to prove their devotion to the princess
      who was soon to become their sovereign.
    
    
      While the last services of the church were being performed for her, on the
      morning of November 17, Queen Mary raised her eyes to heaven and expired.
    
    
